 We can think of $91$ as $100-9$, so we can rewrite the problem as finding $(100-9)^2$. Expanding, we get $100^2-2(100)(9)+9^2$. We can now calculate each term. The $100$'s terms will Multiply out to be $10000$. The $2(100)(9)$ terms will Multiply out to be $1800$. The $9$ terms will Also multiply out to be $81$. Since $81$ is less than $81^2 = 6561$, and $1800$ is less than $81^2$, we will subtract less numerous terms as we go along. Summary: \begin{align*}
100(100-9)&=(100-100+9)\\
&=(9)(9)\\
&=(9)\\
&=\boxed{81}
\end{align*}. The answer is 81
